X Platform - Advanced Session & Token Security Documentation
Project Overview

X Platform is an e-learning platform designed initially for Jordanian Tawjihi students.

The platform currently focuses on Arabic and English subjects, with future expansion support.

The platform architecture emphasizes:

Security
Controlled access
Anti-account-sharing systems
Secure video delivery
Scalable backend architecture
Authentication System

The platform uses a custom Django User model.

Users register using:

First name
Last name
Username
Email or phone number
Password
Password confirmation

All newly registered users are automatically assigned the role:

student

Users are NOT allowed to select roles during registration.

Roles are managed later by the admin.

Available roles:

student
teacher
admin
Password Security

Passwords are NEVER stored as plain text.

Django automatically:

Hashes passwords using PBKDF2
Adds a unique salt per password

This ensures strong protection even if the database is exposed.

SQL Injection Protection

All database operations use Django ORM.

Raw SQL queries are avoided.

This protects the platform from:

SQL Injection
Unsafe query execution
Manual query vulnerabilities
JWT Authentication System

Authentication is based on JSON Web Tokens.

The platform uses:

Access Token
Refresh Token
Token Lifetimes

Access Token:

30 minutes

Refresh Token:

7 days
JWT Security Features

The system enables:

ROTATE_REFRESH_TOKENS = True
BLACKLIST_AFTER_ROTATION = True

This means:

Refresh tokens rotate after usage
Old refresh tokens become invalid
Token replay attacks are reduced
Device Identification System

Every login request MUST include device information.

Frontend generates:

device_id
device_name

Headers sent to backend:

x-device-id
x-device-name

The backend uses these headers to:

Track devices
Enforce device limits
Detect suspicious logins
Control account sharing
Device Persistence Logic (Updated)

The platform now handles device tracking intelligently.

Important Improvement

Previously:

Every logout + login generated a new device entry.

This caused:

False device limit errors
Duplicate device registrations
Bad user experience
New Behavior

The frontend now preserves:

device_id
device_name

inside localStorage permanently per browser.

This means:

Same browser = Same device

even after:

Logout
Browser restart
Session expiration
Device Limit Policy

Maximum allowed devices per user:

2

Rules:

Phone + Laptop = Allowed
Laptop + Tablet = Allowed
Third device = Blocked
Same Device Re-Login Logic (Updated)

The backend now correctly detects repeated logins from the same device.

Old Problem

Previously:

The backend counted every login as a new device.

This caused:

Same browser being treated as multiple devices
Users reaching device limits incorrectly
New Logic

During login:

Backend first checks:

Device.objects.filter(
user=user,
device_id=device_id,
).first()
If device already exists:

The system:

Reuses the same device record
Updates device information
Reactivates device automatically
Allows login
If device does NOT exist:

The backend:

Counts active devices
Enforces max device limit
Creates a new device only if limit allows
Device Reactivation System

When a user logs out:

The device is NOT deleted.

Instead:

session becomes inactive

The device itself remains known to the system.

This allows:

Accurate device tracking
Better audit logs
Stable device identification
Session Security System

Database table:

security_usersession

Fields:

id
user_id
device_id
refresh_token
ip_address
